Support for braking in critical situations is now required
As with the ABS anti-blocking brake system and as it is now happening with ESP stability control, the braking brake apparatus must become a mandatory equipment in the European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and small transporters, for the remaining vehicles a car park period has been set by the end of February 2011.
The European Union's decision aims to improve the protection of the drivers, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exercise more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake maneuver, which recognizes the system using the brake strength carried out by the driver on the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident no longer came to the brake pedal before the collapse, and half of them had not brake fully.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, however, takes up the brake system with maximum power and thus reduces the brake time and thus also the brake distance that a car relays during braking process.
According to a EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents that damage drivers could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistants.
There would be even less accidents - one expects that one fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency brake systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects (by radar or camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time it already exercises a light pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him to increase pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collapse is inevitable, the brake assistant exercises the maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
